## 3. Why Hedera — The Architectural Argument

This is not "we chose Hedera because it's fast." **This architecture is only possible on Hedera.**

### HCS as Command Layer — Not a Receipt Printer

Every other RWA platform logs to a blockchain *after* the fact. Tokenise.Farm uses **HCS as the intent layer**: the farm tokenisation event is submitted to the consensus topic *first*, and the HTS mint transaction is anchored to it. This creates an immutable, regulator-readable, timestamped chain of custody — before the token exists.

For UK agricultural lenders and the HMRC, this matters enormously. It is not marketing. It is evidence.

| Why Hedera Specifically | The Alternative |
|------------------------|-----------------|
| HCS: £0.0001/message, 3-second finality | Ethereum: £2–20/event, 15-second blocks |
| Native scheduled transactions on-chain | Requires off-chain cron jobs or keeper bots |
| Fair ordering — no front-running on farm tokens | MEV attacks possible on EVM chains |
| Enterprise governance (Google, IBM, Boeing as council) | Permissionless chaos — not lender-acceptable |
| HTS: compliance hooks, KYC/freeze built-in | ERC-20: no native compliance layer |

A regulator, lender, or land registry integration **requires** this stack. This is not a technical preference. It is a legal and commercial necessity.

